Riddle: A five-pound steel ball will fall through water at 40 degrees Fahrenheit more quickly than water at 20 degrees Fahrenheit if it is dropped from a height of 45 inches in Jamaica. How is that even doable?
Options:
A) The temperature of stell ball is more consistent with water in 20 degrees Fahrenheit.
B) At 20 degrees Fahrenheit the water would be ice.
C) The temperature of stell ball is more consistent with water in 40 degrees Fahrenheit.
D) None of above.
Choose the correct answer:
(Select one of the above options by typing A, B, C, or D)
Response: A clever riddle!  The correct answer is B) At 20 degrees Fahrenheit the water would be ice.  Since the steel ball is dropped from a height of 45 inches in Jamaica, it doesn't matter what the temperature of the steel ball is, as it will still experience the same air resistance and gravity. The key to the riddle is the phrase "water at 20 degrees Fahrenheit".  At 20 degrees Fahrenheit, water would be in its solid state, i.e., ice. Since the steel ball is falling through water at 40 degrees Fahrenheit, it will fall through the liquid water, which has a higher density than ice. Therefore, the steel ball will fall more quickly through the water at 40 degrees Fahrenheit than through the ice at 20 degrees Fahrenheit.
Answer: B
